eglected transformative view, which this book expounds, stressed the importance of democratic beliefs and ideology, whereas the elite conception minimized their significance. The transformative perspective highlighted the radicalizing, dynamic effects of movements that attempt to realize democratic values and act upon democratic ideologies, while the better-known elite model depicted democracy in static terms and as institutionally stable. Despite the sharp contrasts, both perspectives were part of Schumpeter's complex and deeply conservative response to political change in his lifetime. Precisely because he viewed democracy as a potent transformative social force, he labored strenuously to theorize a form of society in which elites could restrain the pace and nature of democratic change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDemocracy. 0aDemocratie. 0aDemokratie. 0aDémocratie. 0aElite (Social sciences). 0aPolitik. 0aTheorie. 0aÉlite (Sciences sociales). 4aDemocracy. 4aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General. 4aSchumpeter, Joseph Alois, 1883-1950 -- Contributions in political science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Social Science eBook Packagez9783110353556oZDB-23-HCI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831104422050 cprintz978067418641540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067418643940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674186439423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674186439/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard Univer